he Nomadic Alternative – here discussed in detail for the first time – through to his final novel Utz. In subjecting his work to such analysis, the study uncovers a striking thematic commonality in Chatwin’s oeuvre: his work is fundamentally preoccupied with the subject of human restlessness. This volume provides detailed insight into Chatwin’s treatment of the subject in his work, identifying and discussing the biographical and philosophical sources of this defining preoccupation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aTravelers' writings, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aBruce Chatwin.  aIn Patagonia.  aOn the Black Hill.  aThe Nomadic Alternative.  aThe Songlines.  aThe Viceroy of Ouidah.  aasceticism.  acollector's anxiety.  agoodness of man.  aillusory goals.  apsychology of exile.  arestlessness.  atravel writing.  awriterly tendency.1 aChatwin, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612977240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129772/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles